When I went to see Wonder Woman with my friend, I came out of the theatre babbling about how Diana is so strong and fierce and brave, and how she made me look forward to my next run, my next gym session, so I can work even harder and make myself stronger and faster and maybe, one day, I could be like her. I'm seventeen, and all I wanted in that moment was to *be* Wonder Woman. 
When I said all this to my dad, ending with, "from now on, I'm training like Wonder Woman", he told me that what I was feeling was how he used to feel about superheroes when he was four. And how my brother felt about superheroes when he was six. I've been watching Iron Man Armoured Adventures and Justice League and reading Spiderman and Captain America comics with my brothers since I was old enough to understand the stories, and it's taken me until I'm seventeen to feel the same way they felt from the very start. Because as a girl growing up with Spiderman and Captain America and Iron Man and The Flash and Superman and Batman and Green Lantern, I never had what they had - a character I could identify with. 

That's literally all it takes.

Comment:
*SPOILERS*

Not a bad film. Certainly the best of the DCEU so far (I haven't seen Suicide Squad). Here's what I would change:

1. The Beginning needs to be better. It doesn't really get interesting until after they leave the island. It felt so cliched in the beginning with lines like, "She's a child," and, "She won't be a child forever."

2. If Steve Trevor really is British (I don't recall him indicating he was American in any way like he is in the comics) then he should have a British accent.

3. Since war is a big theme in the film, it would've been good to see her accept having to make a Sophie's Choice in war. She goes around saying, "This is wrong," a little too much in the film and it gets tired. And then, when confronted with a problem, she's able to solve it (like the trench warfare).

It would've been great if she was shown to be forced to have to make such a choice and weeps as a result. She then realizes that this is the truth of war that her mother warned her about.

4. I would've preferred she defeated Ares the same way WW defeated him in the George Perez reboot. That was so much more meaningful.

5. I don't mind Ares looking the way he does in human form, but in god form, why does he still look like that British Actor?

Comment:
Did she really need a character arc based around reflecting a bullet? She has so many different backstories to choose from or draw inspiration from, but instead of leaving the island to see the glory that is the world and going from fry cook to (honorary) ambassador as she sees the best and worst of humanity, all while holding onto the ideals represented by the gifts bestowed upon her, we get invaders with guns as a 'call to adventure'. Sure, okay.

I'm entirely for a dark and dramatic storyline, but levity and pacing is needed for such stories lest you end up with Liefeld-esque narratives. In other words, all drama is depressing, but drama mixed with comedy or exciting action (requiring achievements and an overall sense of victory) is gripping and even more dramatic. To put it in another frame, if you are watching a fight, it's more gripping and heartbreaking when they both fight well then one loses/dies than it is when one guy mercilessly pounds someone much weaker.

I will say that the music in the trailer was amazing.

Comment:
Some bits I've managed to spot and some observations:

Steve is being interrogated with the lasso of truth on him (can just barely be seen in the lower right corner of the screen).

The sword the guy is wielding near the end appears to be Diana's own sword, so she was likely disarmed at some point before that scene, and was now in the process of reacquiring it.  Certainly she has to have been on the short end of the stick at some point in the movie for proper audience anxiety and a situation to dig herself out of (78 Supes had the kryptonite necklace around his neck), and the sword being in the villains' possession hints at that.

99% certain she is not flying at the end, but has just reached the apogee of a huge jump and then the lightening may from that point contribute in suspending her

She's charging past/thru quite a bit of rapidly erupting/collapsing material before the big jump so perhaps the crossed bracers are in the process of trying to absorb the brunt of some massive energy outburst from below

Would love to see a scene in Justice League where she and the Flash are competing at bullet time reactions - he'd readily win but she would be seen to  be at a not-insignificant speed, and anyone else in the room would appear to be frozen

Comment: Look, if this is yet another case of the trailer drawing us into another crappy DC Movie... I'm done with the Extended universe. I'm not going to watch Justice League Part 1, nor anything coming after it, if Wonder Woman sucks. I'm sick and tired of Zack Snyder banking on the cinematic universe reputation that Marvel garnered, but there is a reason why Marvel made it successful... They made actually universally accepted and good movies. Movies that know exactly what it wants to be, and not trying to be something it's not. After Man of Steel, Batman V Superman aka Pot vs Kettle, and Suicide Squad... I would really like an actually good movie out of DC for once. I don't go see DC, expecting it to be just like another Marvel movie. I go to see DC, to see DC films like The Dark Knight, or even the Christopher Reeves Superman Films. Back when DC did know how to make a good movie, and Marvel didn't have the Cinematic Universe to go on. So, if it turns out to be yet another polarizing movie with most people hating it, and since there will be feminists possibly defending it, people who actually like it and try to tell us you have to watch it multiple times to understand. If that's the case, then it really doesn't make sense. And how much do you want to bet that there's going to be an extended version that's only slightly better and the obligatory R rated cut? Cause Zack Snyder doesn't believe in the R rated theatrical release... Despite Deadpool being a huge success with it's R rating.

Comment:
I have to say, I went into this trailer very abrasive. BVS and the first WW trailer didn't impress me, and I hadn't had my fill of seeing Gal on screen for me to be fully behind her casting. In fact, the whole DCEU as a whole has left a bad taste in my mouth (including the JL trailer).

Now, THIS TRAILER is the first where I was *squealing like an 11 year old girl seeing a dick for the first time.* XD. Seriously though, I couldn't contain my excitement when I saw the first shot of Diana on the cliff's edge seeing Steve Trevor's plane go down, I mean THE COLORS! And hearing WW proclaim her morals and beliefs about defending humankind, OH! Music to my ears! If that wasn't enough, the fanatic in me went BANANAS when I saw her blocking bullets with her bracelets,  MY GOD THE GLORY!!!

Now that I'm on this high from watching the trailer for what may be the first DCEU movie to finally do its characters justice, oh man, say it with me now:

*PLEASE DON'T SUCK. PLEASE DON'T SUCK. PLEASE DON'T SUCK.*

Title: WONDER WOMAN - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment:
I know this has been said before, but screw it I'll say it myself:

I consider myself a fan of both Marvel and DC. However, I've found that Warner Bros' attempts to cash in on the success of the MCU have led to three complete messes of films due to bad writing and inconsistent editing, despite the admittedly decent cinematography and acting (most of the time). By and large, I think Marvel has been making superior movies for the past eight years with their own peaks and nadirs, but still more enjoyable to watch than the DC Extended Universe.

Batman v. Superman is a dead horse beaten to a bloody pulp already, but the fact remains that it still suffered from a dumb plot that utterly failed to capture the meaning behind the Bats/Supes fight in The Dark Knight Returns in any capacity, shoddy editing (especially in the theatrical cut, though the Ultimate Edition fixed this to an extent), weak performances by everyone who wasn't named Ben Affleck, Jeremy Irons or Gal Gadot, and a tacked on climax with Doomsday that was used FAR too early in the franchise for the Death of Superman storyline to have any kind of weight to it.

Suicide Squad, meanwhile, suffered from a plot with more holes in it than an everyday M. Night Shyamalan film, imbalanced characterization for the main characters (anyone who wasn't Deadshot, Rick Flagg, Harley Quinn, or Amanda Waller was almost completely sidelined), constant focus on probably THE worst Joker performance I've ever seen in any DC media, and the simple fact that it served no purpose than to give us that one scene at the very end where Bruce gets the files for Aquaman, Cyborg, and The Flash from Waller, which probably could have happened in a mid-credits scene in BvS if they wanted to. Oh wait, they don't do mid-credits scenes, because that would make them too similar to Marvel, AND WE CAN'T HAVE THAT NOW CAN WE!

However, this trailer has me legitimately hyped. Gadot was one of the best parts about BvS (despite her abysmal total screen time), and this trailer got me excited for her chance in the spotlight as Wonder Woman. It also seems like the writers might actually know how to treat this character, so I'm excited for that.

Overall, good trailer. Now WB, please don't screw this up again, or else I'm never going to bother with your DC movies ever again.

This is DC's big chance to gain the upper hand in at least one segment and to be honest - the trailer doesn't look that good. It comes off like a female version of Thor combined with Captain America: The First Avenger. 

It just lacks a distinctive atmosphere and face, but maybe that's just me.

Anyway, I hope the movie delivers.¬†DC and WB¬†can't really¬†afford to fuck this up. If they do, DCU will positively remain and be remembered as the "also-ran" of this current generation of comic-book movies. How do you fuck up Superman and Batman first forging their legendary bond on the big screen, a bond upon which much of comic culture is BUILT in the shadow of? How do you fuck that up? Comment: This looks VERY good so far, but it's hard not to feel wary after the DCEU's past output. I was cautious about Batman v Superman from the start (which was proven entirely warranted once I saw that baffling disaster), but I was genuinely excited about Suicide Squad, only to find it a frustrating, sloppy and surprisingly dull mess. And to be clear I'm not going in wanting to hate on these movies- I LOVE these characters, I LOVE the DC Universe, and I desperately WANT to like these movies, but so far they just haven't managed to get it together. I've been wanting to see a Wonder Woman movie for ages now, and I'm willing to let myself get excited for this one in spite of those recent disappointments. But for me at least this is their last chance to get me on board- if they blow it again on this one, this absolute can't-miss project that has so much going for it, I'm calling it quits on the DCEU entirely.

Title: WONDER WOMAN - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment:
Amazing. WB learned from their Doomsday trailer. Seeing it for the second time, we see Diana's sense of duty, the warrior, the compassion she feels for the world and at the start, the pain of walking away from it all. Etta Candy is funny, Steve will undoubtedly provide humour and some of the action. We see enough of Diana to know what she's like. We know Danny Huston's German officer is going to be an antagonist but we don't know WHO he is, nor what he plans to achieve, David Thewlis is still absent which means they are probably saving him for the movie. At this point Danny is either Ares/Steppenwolf and David is Zeus/Steppenwolf. 

We see brighter scenes with more colour, great action and what may be the new tone of the DCEU. This is the movie to make or break the DCEU and I cannot wait to see the final trailer and then the movie itself. June 2017 cannot come sooner.
